obedimy]], Russian engineer (b. 1921)\n*  2014   &ndash; [[Jesse Winchester]], American singer-songwriter, guitarist, and producer (b. 1944)\n*[[2015]] &ndash; [[Jimmy Gunn]], American football player (b. 1948)\n*  2015   &ndash; [[Muhammad Kamaruzzaman]], Bangladeshi journalist and politician (b. 1952)\n*  2015   &ndash; [[Fran\u00e7ois Maspero]], French journalist and author (b. 1932)\n*  2015   &ndash; [[Hanut Singh (soldier)|Hanut Singh]], Indian general (b. 1933)\n*  2015   &ndash; [[Tekena Tamuno]], Nigerian historian and academic (b. 1932)\n*[[2017]] &ndash; [[J. Geils]], American singer and guitarist (b. 1946)\n*  2017   &ndash; [[Mark Wainberg]], Canadian researcher and HIV/AIDS activist (b. 1945)\n<!--Do not add people without Wikipedia articles to this list. Do not trust \"this year in history\" websites for accurate date information. Do not link multiple occurrences of the same year, just link the first occurrence.-->\n\n==Holidays and observances==\n*Christian [[feast day]]:\n**[[Antipas of Pergamum]] ([[Greek Orthodox Church]])\n**[[Gemma Galgani]]\n**[[Godeberta]]\n**[[Guthlac of Crowland]]\n**[[George Selwyn (bishop of Lichfield)|George Selwyn]] ([[Anglicanism]])\n**[[Stanislaus of Szczepan\u00f3w]]\n**[[April 11 (Eastern Orthodox liturgics)]]\n*[[Juan Santamar\u00eda Day]], anniversary of his death in the [[Second Battle of Rivas]]. ([[Costa Rica]])\n*[[International Louie Louie Day]]\n*[[World Parkinson's Day]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/april/11 BBC: On This Day]\n* {{NYT On this day|month=04|day=11}}\n* [http://canadachannel.ca/todayincanadianhistory/index.php/April_11 Today in Canadian History]\n{{months}}\n\n[[Category:Days of the year]]\n[[Category:April]]\n", "name_user": "213.200.15.248", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/April_11"}
{"title_page": "Lim Yi Wei", "text_new": "{{short description|Malaysian politician (born 1989)}}\n{{No footnotes|date=April 2020}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Lim Yi Wei}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Lin (surname)|Lim (\u6797)]]}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name             = Lim Yi Wei\n| image            = Lim Yi Wei (April 2020).jpg\n| native_name      = {{nobold|\u6797\u6021\u5a01}}\n| native_name_lang = zh-my\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1989|11|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Ipoh, Perak]], Malaysia\n| honorific-prefix = [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Malay titles#Other salutations|Puan]]\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLA]]\n| assembly         = Selangor State Legislative\n| constituency_AM  = [[Kampung Tunku (state constituency)|Kampung Tunku]]\n| term_start       = 26 June 2018\n| term_end         = \n| predecessor      = Lau Weng San\n| majority         = 30,444 ([[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]])\n| party            = [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP)\n| otherparty       = [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH)\n| alma_mater       = [[HKUST Business School]]\n| occupation       = [[Politician]]\n| profession       = \n| website          = {{url|https://fb.com/LimYiWei.MY/|Fan Page}}\n}}\n\n'''Lim Yi Wei''' ([[Chinese language|Chinese]]: \u6797\u6021\u5a01; [[pinyin]]: L\u00edn y\u00ed w\u0113i; born 27 November 1989) is a Malaysian politician from the [[Democratic Action Party|Democratic Action Party (DAP)]], one of the four component parties of the [[Pakatan Harapan|Pakatan Harapan (PH)]] coalition. She is currently the assembly woman of the [[Selangor State Legislative Assembly]] for [[Kampung Tunku (state constituency)|Kampung Tunku]] constituency in the state of [[Selangor]].\n\nShe is also division chief for DAP Socialist Youth (DAPSY) Damansara and organising secretary of the DAP Selangor women's wing.\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nLim is the eldest of three children born to Lim Chin Chye, a retired lecturer at Institut Perguruan (IPG) Sultan Abdul Halim, Sungai Petani, and Wong Wai Ping, a retired teacher SK La Salle, Ipoh. Outside politics, she played some university rugby. She also has a YouTube channel of piano covers.\n\n== Education ==\n\nLim completed her primary education at SK Marian Convent, Ipoh and her secondary education at SMK (P) Methodist Ipoh before taking the [[Sijil Tinggi Persekolahan Malaysia|Sijil Tinggi Persekolahan Malaysia (STPM)]] at SMK Methodist (ACS) Ipoh.\n\nShe graduated from [[The Hong Kong University of Science & Technology Business School|the Hong Kong University of Science & Technology (HKUST)]] with a Bachelor of Business Administration (BBA) in Finance on a scholarship sponsored by Kerry Holdings Ltd. As an international student representative in the HKUST Business School Undergraduate Representatives\u2019 Committee, she helped establish the Business Cohort Community (BCC) to help integrate freshmen into the varsity community. In 2013, she ran an emergency fundraiser in HKUST to support Typhoon Haiyan disaster victims. The 2-day fundraiser raised HKD 75,000 (~USD 9,600).\n\n== Early career ==\n\nUpon graduating, Lim worked as a conference producer covering Asia at [[Incisive Media]]\u2019s Hong Kong office. Her portfolio included two brands: Waterstechnology, covering financial technology and data for capital markets; and Risk.net, covering risk management, derivatives and regulation. Her flagship conference was the Asia Pacific Financial Information Conference (APFIC) 2014 and 2015, featuring technology providers such as Thomson Reuters, Bloomberg and Markit; exchanges such as CME Group, Singapore Exchange (SGX) and the Hong Kong Stock Exchange (HKEx); and buy-side and sell-side firms across Asia. Lim also pioneered the first Asia Pacific blockchain training course for capital markets players, Blockchain Bootcamp, held in Singapore in May 2016. Despite having left Incisive for Malaysian politics by then, the bootcamp has been replicated in Hong Kong and Sydney, with a subsequent Blockchain Applications workshop held in Singapore in March 2017.\n\n== Political career ==\n\nSpurred by the Hong Kong Umbrella Movement, Lim decided to return to Malaysia to participate in Malaysian politics. She began her political career as the political secretary of [[Tony Pua]], then MP of Petaling Jaya Utara (now renamed [[Damansara (Selangor federal constituency)|Damansara]]) and DAP National Publicity Secretary. She actively campaigned in the [[2016 Sarawak state election|2016 Sarawak State Elections]] for the [[Bukit Goram]] state seat, as well as the 2016 Sungai Besar by-elections. In September 2016, Lim was appointed as a Councillor for the [[Petaling Jaya City Council|Petaling Jaya City Council (MBPJ)]]. She championed issues such as youth and women empowerment and mental health, organising various forums and lectures. Lim was nominated as a DAP candidate for the [[Kampung Tunku (state constituency)|Kampung Tunku]] state constituency during the [[2018 Malaysian general election|2018 General Elections]]. She won the seat with a majority of 30,444 votes, beating [[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]]\u2019s Tan Gim Tuan as well as becoming Kampung Tunku\u2019s first female representative. At the age of 28 she was also one of the youngest candidates to stand for elections in Selangor. After GE14, Lim campaigned actively in the 2019 Cameron Highlands by-elections. Despite being an ethnic Chinese politician, she was posted to the [[Malays (ethnic group)|Malay]]-majority [[Jelai (state constituency)|Jelai state constituency]] and stationed in FELDA Sungai Koyan 3.\n\n== Issues and causes ==\n\nIssues brought by Lim through speeches, writing and programmes as well in the State Assembly include: mental health, youth and women empowerment, civic education, national unity, and culture. Lim is a strong supporter of local cultural efforts such as the awardwinning SK Kampung Tunku Pawana Tari traditional dance team and the Khuan Loke Dragon & Lion Dance Association, which originates from Sungai Way New Village. The Kampung Tunku 2018 Malaysia Day celebration, themed \u201cKampung Tunku Kampungku\u201d (\u201cKampung Tunku, My Village\u201d), featured an exhibition of Kampung Tunku's history and notable residents, including the National Laureate Usman Awang and Yap Ah Loy's descendants. Residents also submitted stories and photos growing up and living in Kampung Tunku. Performances and food were provided by local residents and traders. Lim is currently supporting the Selangor Rugby Union (Malay: Kesatuan Ragbi Selangor; KRS) women's team and the national women's rugby team through contributing funds and raising awareness about women's rugby.\n\n== Election results ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:90%\"\n|+'''[[Selangor State Legislative Assembly]]'''\n!Year\n!Constituency\n! colspan=\"2\" |\n!Votes\n!Pct\n! colspan=\"2\" |Opponent(s)\n!Votes\n!Pct\n!Ballots cast\n!Majority\n!Turnout\n|-\n|[[2018 Selangor state election|2018]]\n|[[Kampung Tunku (state constituency)|Kampung Tunku]]\n| {{Party shading/Democratic Action Party}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Lim Yi Wei'''}} ('''[[Democratic Action Party (Malaysia)|DAP]]''')\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |'''34,477'''\n|'''89.53%'''\n| {{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Tan Gim Tuan ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |'''4,033'''\n|10.47%\n|38,821\n|'''30,444'''\n|79.88%\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* \"[https://www.malaysiakini.com/letters/376073 DAP: Does EC chair think current voter registration system is efficient?\"] ''[[Malaysiakini]]''. 17 Mar 2017. Retrieved 10 December 2019.\n* \"[http://www.malaysiakini.com/news/394988 Welcoming the hopeful\"] ''[[Malaysiakini]]''. 13 Sep 2017. Retrieved 10 December 2019.\n* \"[https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/opinion/2017/10/22/can-the-midd