{"title_page": "Pasar pagi", "text_new": "[[File:Pasar Keputran Surabaya.JPG|thumb|300px|Pasar Keputran, one of ''pasar pagi'' in [[Surabaya]], Indonesia.]]\n'''''Pasar pagi''''' ([[Malay language|Malay]]/[[Indonesian language|Indonesian]], lit.: \"morning market\") is a type of traditional [[Market (place)|market]] found in [[Indonesia]] and [[Malaysia]], sometimes classified as a [[wet market]].<ref name=\"NST1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nst.com.my/opinion/leaders/2020/04/582913/nst-leader-new-normal |title=NST Leader: The new normal |publisher=[[New Straits Times]]|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=10 April 2020</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/470416 |date=1 April 2019 |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nst.com.my/lifestyle/sunday-vibes/2018/08/402996/batu-pahats-charming-hotel-57-offers-guest-quirky-experience |title=Batu Pahat's charming Hotel 57 offers guest a quirky experience |date=19 August 2018 |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ban\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/22/negri-hawkers-food-trucks-to-operate-7am-8pm-from-march-24 |publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]] |title=Negri hawkers, food trucks to operate 7am-8pm from March 24 |date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Operating hours==\n[[File:PasarPagi002.jpg|thumb|''Pasar pagi'' in Malaysia.]]\n''Pasar pagi'' mostly operate from early morning to the afternoon.<ref name=\"JP-market\">{{cite news | title = Weekly 5: Traditional markets around the clock | newspaper = The Jakarta Post | date = 19 December 2014 | url = http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2014/12/19/weekly-5-traditional-markets-around-clock.html}}</ref> Nevertheless, there is also a related traditional market called ''[[pasar malam]]'' (lit.: \"night market\"). The difference between ''pasar pagi'' and ''pasar malam'' is in its operating hours \u2014 ''pasar pagi'' opens early in the morning from dawn to the noon every day, approximately from 04:00 to 12:00. While ''pasar malam'' opens at night, approximately from 17:00 to 22:00, and only on selected days of a week. \n\nThe type of goods being sold is also quite different. ''Pasar pagi'' is where many housewives, domestic helps and local folks appear to shop their daily needs, mostly uncooked fresh [[Greengrocer|produce]]. The things which are on sale are usually fresh daily produce, including [[fruits]], [[vegetables]], [[spices]], [[Fish as food|fish]], [[meat]], [[Egg as food|eggs]], and all kinds of daily products. While ''pasar malam'' is more to cater a leisurely shopping and eating-out activity, selling ready to eat food, snacks, clothing and various knick-knacks.\n\n==Indonesia==\nIn Indonesia, practically all traditional markets are ''pasar pagi'', open from early in the [[dawn]] to mid day. Often the stalls are temporarily overflow occupying nearby streets around the marketplace \u2014 which normally open for traffic in other hours of the day. They sell fresh produces, such as vegetables, fruits, chicken, meat and fish. The major ''pasar pagi'' in [[Jakarta]] are Pasar Pagi Mangga Dua, Pasar Induk Kramat Jati, [[Pasar Minggu]] and [[Senen|Pasar Senen]]. Pasar Minggu specialized on fruits and vegetables, while Pasar Kue Subuh in Senen specialized on selling ''[[kue]]'', as they offer a rich variety of traditional Indonesian snack, open every ''subuh'' (dawn).<ref name=\"JP-market\"/>\n\n==Malaysia==\nIn Malaysia, one of the biggest ''pasar pagi'' is at Pasar Pudu at [[Pudu, Kuala Lumpur|Pudu]] and Jalan Pasar at [[Chow Kit]] area in [[Kuala Lumpur]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Chow Kit\u2019s lively markets | date = 31 October 2014 | newspaper = The Star | url = http://www.thestar.com.my/news/community/2014/10/31/chow-kits-lively-markets-brave-the-noisy-crowd-for-a-unique-shopping-experience/}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, all wet markets (including pasar pagi) were temporarily banned from operating due to the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"ban\"/>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Bazaar]]\n* [[Hawker centre]], open-air complexes in Malaysia and Singapore housing many stalls that sell a variety of inexpensive food\n* ''[[Kopi tiam]]'', literally a \"coffee shop\"\n* [[Market (place)]]\n* ''[[Pasar malam]]'', (night market)\n* [[Retail]]\n* [[Wet market]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Indonesian culture]]\n[[Category:Malaysian culture]]\n[[Category:Singaporean culture]]\n[[Category:Malay words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Retail markets]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Pasar Keputran Surabaya.JPG|thumb|300px|Pasar Keputran, one of ''pasar pagi'' in [[Surabaya]], Indonesia.]]\n'''''Pasar pagi''''' ([[Malay language|Malay]]/[[Indonesian language|Indonesian]], lit.: \"morning market\") is a type of traditional [[Market (place)|market]] found in [[Indonesia]] and [[Malaysia]], sometimes classified as a [[wet market]].<ref name=\"NST1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nst.com.my/opinion/leaders/2020/04/582913/nst-leader-new-normal |title=NST Leader: The new normal |publisher=[[New Straits Times]]|date=10 April 2020|accessdate=10 April 2020</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/470416 |date=1 April 2019 |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nst.com.my/lifestyle/sunday-vibes/2018/08/402996/batu-pahats-charming-hotel-57-offers-guest-quirky-experience |title=Batu Pahat's charming Hotel 57 offers guest a quirky experience |date=19 August 2018 |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ban\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/22/negri-hawkers-food-trucks-to-operate-7am-8pm-from-march-24 |publisher=[[The Star]] |title=Negri hawkers, food trucks to operate 7am-8pm from March 24 |date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Operating hours==\n[[File:PasarPagi002.jpg|thumb|''Pasar pagi'' in Malaysia.]]\n''Pasar pagi'' mostly operate from early morning to the afternoon.<ref name=\"JP-market\">{{cite news | title = Weekly 5: Traditional markets around the clock | newspaper = The Jakarta Post | date = 19 December 2014 | url = http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2014/12/19/weekly-5-traditional-markets-around-clock.html}}</ref> Nevertheless, there is also a related traditional market called ''[[pasar malam]]'' (lit.: \"night market\"). The difference between ''pasar pagi'' and ''pasar malam'' is in its operating hours \u2014 ''pasar pagi'' opens early in the morning from dawn to the noon every day, approximately from 04:00 to 12:00. While ''pasar malam'' opens at night, approximately from 17:00 to 22:00, and only on selected days of a week. \n\nThe type of goods being sold is also quite different. ''Pasar pagi'' is where many housewives, domestic helps and local folks appear to shop their daily needs, mostly uncooked fresh [[Greengrocer|produce]]. The things which are on sale are usually fresh daily produce, including [[fruits]], [[vegetables]], [[spices]], [[Fish as food|fish]], [[meat]], [[Egg as food|eggs]], and all kinds of daily products. While ''pasar malam'' is more to cater a leisurely shopping and eating-out activity, selling ready to eat food, snacks, clothing and various knick-knacks.\n\n==Indonesia==\nIn Indonesia, practically all traditional markets are ''pasar pagi'', open from early in the [[dawn]] to mid day. Often the stalls are temporarily overflow occupying nearby streets around the marketplace \u2014 which normally open for traffic in other hours of the day. They sell fresh produces, such as vegetables, fruits, chicken, meat and fish. The major ''pasar pagi'' in [[Jakarta]] are Pasar Pagi Mangga Dua, Pasar Induk Kramat Jati, [[Pasar Minggu]] and [[Senen|Pasar Senen]]. Pasar Minggu specialized on fruits and vegetables, while Pasar Kue Subuh in Senen specialized on selling ''[[kue]]'', as they offer a rich variety of traditional Indonesian snack, open every ''subuh'' (dawn).<ref name=\"JP-market\"/>\n\n==Malaysia==\nIn Malaysia, one of the biggest ''pasar pagi'' is at Pasar Pudu at [[Pudu, Kuala Lumpur|Pudu]] and Jalan Pasar at [[Chow Kit]] area in [[Kuala Lumpur]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Chow Kit\u2019s lively markets | date = 31 October 2014 | newspaper = The Star | url = http://www.thestar.com.my/news/community/2014/10/31/chow-kits-lively-markets-brave-the-noisy-crowd-for-a-unique-shopping-experience/}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, all wet markets (including pasar pagi) were temporarily banned from operating due to the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"ban\"/>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Bazaar]]\n* [[Hawker centre]], open-air complexes in Malaysia and Singapore housing many stalls that sell a variety of inexpensive food\n* ''[[Kopi tiam]]'', literally a \"coffee shop\"\n* [[Market (place)]]\n* ''[[Pasar malam]]'', (night market)\n* [[Retail]]\n* [[Wet market]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Indonesian culture]]\n[[Category:Malaysian culture]]\n[[Category:Singaporean culture]]\n[[Category:Malay words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Retail markets]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toStar (disambiguation)(link changed toThe Star (Malaysia)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pasar_pagi"}
{"title_page": "Francis D'Souza (politician)", "text_new": "{{about|Indian politician|Canadian TV news anchor|Francis D'Souza}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Francis D'Souza\n| birth_name = Francisco Casimiro Jer\u00f3nimo Agnelo Pinto de Souza\n\n|image = {{CSS image crop\n|Image = M. Venkaiah Naidu addressing a press conference on 47th International Film Festival of India (IFFI), in New Delhi.jpg\n|bSize = 1100\n|cWidth = 180\n|cHeight = 220\n|oTop = 310\n|oLeft = 618\n|Location=center\n}}\n\n| caption            = D'Souza at [[International Film Festival of India|IFFI]] [[47th International Film Festival of India|2016]]\n| birth_date ={{birth date|1954|10|04|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Mapusa]], [[Bardez]], [[Goa]], India\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|2019|02|14|1954|10|04}} \n| death_place = \n| office = [[List of Deputy Chief Ministers of Goa|Deputy Chief Minister of Goa]]\n| constituency = [[Mapusa (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Mapusa]]\n| term_start = 9 March 2012\n| term_end = 14 March 2017\n| predecessor = [[Wilfred de Souza]]\n| successor = [[Sudin Dhavalikar]]<br/>[[Vijai Sardesai]]\n| office1             = [[Goa Legislative Assembly|Member of Goa Legislative Assembly]]\n| constituency1       = [[Mapusa (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Mapusa]]\n| term_start1         = 1999\n| term_end1           = 2019\n| predecessor1  = [[Surendra Sirsat]]\n| successor1    = [[Joshua D'Souza]]\n| office2 = \n| constituency2 = \n| term_start2 =\n| predecessor2 =\n| successor2 =\n| party  = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n| otherparty = [[Goa Rajiv Congress Party]]\n| spouse = \n| children = [[Joshua D'Souza]]\n| occupation = [[Lawyer]]<br>[[Politician]]\n| father = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n| date =  |\n| year =  |\n| source =\n}}\n'''Francisco Casimiro Jer\u00f3nimo Agnelo Pinto de Souza''' or '''Francis Dsouza''' (4 October 1954 \u2013 14 February 2019) was an Indian Politician from [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) who served as the [[List of Deputy Chief Ministers of Goa|Deputy Chief Minister]] of the Indian State of [[Goa]]. He contested from [[Mapusa (Vidhan Sabha constituency)]] as an independent unsuccessfully in 1989.\n\n==Biography==\nD'Souza was first elected to the [[Goa Legislative Assembly]] in 1999 as the [[Goa Rajiv Congress Party]]'s candidate and later in 2002, 2007, 2012 and 2017 as the [[BJP]] candidate from the [[Mapusa]] constituency.<ref>[http://www.goavidhansabha.gov.in/member-election-detail.php?id=67&flag=CM Shri. Francis Dsouza Previous Election Details | Goa Legislative Assembly<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He was appointed Deputy Chief Minister when BJP formed a government in 2012 under [[Manohar Parrikar]]'s leadership and remained [[List of Deputy Chief Ministers of Goa|Deputy Chief Minister]] when [[Laxmikant Parsekar]] became the Chief Minister. He was also front-runner to succeed [[Manohar Parrikar]] as the chief minister.<ref>[http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/goa-deputy-chief-minister-francis-dsouza-threatens-to-quit-if-not-made-chief-minister/1/399695.html Goa Deputy Chief Minister Francis D'Souza threatens to quit if not made CM]</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/politics/francis-dsouza-falls-in-line-parsekar-is-new-bjp-goa-cm/ | title=Laxmikant Parsekar sworn in as new Goa CM, Francis D\u2019Souza falls in line | date=9 November 2014 | first=Shalini | last=Nair | newspaper=The Indian Express | accessdate=27 November 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, he landed into a controversy after publicly declaring that [[India]] is a [[Hindu nationalism|Hindu nation]] and he was a ''Christian-Hindu''.<ref>{{cite news|title=India is already a Hindu nation: Goa Deputy CM Francis D\u2019Souza|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/07/india-is-already-a-hindu-nation-goa-deputy-cm-francis-dsouza/|accessdate=27 July 2014|agency=IANS|publisher=news.biharprabha.com|date=25 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nD'Souza died on 14 February 2019 at the age of 64 following a battle with cancer.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://goachronicle.com/goa-bjps-christian-face-francis-dsouza-no-more/ |title=Goa BJP's Christian face Francis D'Souza no more |date=2019-02-14 |website=Goa Chronicle |language=en-US |access-date=2019-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.devdiscourse.com/article/national/381692-francis-dsouza-former-goa-deputy-cm-bjp-mla-dies-at-64 |title=Francis D'Souza, former Goa deputy CM, BJP MLA dies at 64 |website=Devdiscourse News |language=en |access-date=2019-02-14}}</ref>\n\n== Positions held ==\n\n* 1985 - Elected as the Councillor of Mapusa Municipal Council.\n* 1986-1988 - President of Mapusa Municipal Council.\n* 1995 - Elected as the Councillor of Mapusa Municipal Council.\n* 1998-2000 Chairman of Mapusa Municipal Council.\n* 1999 - Cabinet Minister of Law, Election and Urban Development\n* 2000-2002 - Cabinet Minister of Judiciary and Labour & Employment till\n* 2002-2005 - Cabinet Minister of Information Technology, Law & Judiciary, Legislative Affairs and Craftsmen Training.\n* 2012-2014 - Cabinet Minister of Urban Development, Revenue and Craftsmen Training\n* 2014-2019 - Deputy Chief Minister, Cabinet Minister of Health, Revenue, Town and Country Planning, Urban Development and Law, Legislative Affairs\n* 2017-2019 - Cabinet Minister of Urban Development, Law and Judiciary, Legislative Affairs and Provedoria.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:D'Souza, Francis}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deputy chief ministers of Goa]]\n[[Category:People from Mapusa]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Goa]]\n[[Category:Goa MLAs 1999\u20132002]]\n[[Category:Goa MLAs 2002\u20132007]]\n[[Category:Goa MLAs 2007\u20132012]]\n[[Category:Goa MLAs 2012\u20132017]]\n[[Category:Goa MLAs 2017\u2013]]\n[[Category:Goa Rajiv Congress Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Indian Roman Catholics]]\n\n\n{{BJP-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{about|Indian politician|Canadian TV news anchor|Francis D'Souza}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Francis D'Souza\n| birth_name = Francisco Casimiro Jer\u00f3nimo Agnelo Pinto de Souza\n\n|image = {{CSS image crop\n|Image = M. Venkaiah Naidu addressing a press conference on 47th International Film Festival of India (IFFI), in New Delhi.jpg\n|bSize = 1100\n|cWidth = 180\n|cHeight = 220\n|oTop = 310\n|oLeft = 618\n|Location=center\n}}\n\n| caption            = D'Souza at [[International Film Festival of India|IFFI]] [[47th International Film Festival of India|2016]]\n| birth_date ={{birth date|1954|10|04|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Mapusa]], [[Bardez]], [[Goa]], India\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|2019|02|14|1954|10|04}} \n| death_place = \n| office = [[List of Deputy Chief Ministers of Goa|Deputy Chief Minister of Goa]]\n| constituency = [[Mapusa (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Mapusa]]\n| term_start = 9 March 2012\n| term_end = 14 March 2017\n| predecessor = [[Wilfred de Souza]]\n| successor = [[Sudin Dhavalikar]]<br/>[[Vijai Sardesai]]\n| office1             = [[Goa Legislative Assembly|Member of Goa Legislative Assembly]]\n| constituency1       = [[Mapusa (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Mapusa]]\n| term_start1         = 1999\n| term_end1           = 2019\n| predecessor1  = [[Surendra Sirsat]]\n| successor1    = [[Joshua D'Souza]]\n| office2 = \n| constituency2 = \n| term_start2 =\n| predecessor2 =\n| successor2 =\n| party  = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n| otherparty = [[Goa Rajiv Congress Party]]\n| spouse = \n| children = [[Joshua D'Souza]]\n| occupation = [[Lawyer]]<br>[[Politician]]\n| father = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n| date =  |\n| year =  |\n| source =\n}}\n'''Francisco Casimiro Jer\u00f3nimo Agnelo Pinto de Souza''' or '''Francis Dsouza''' (4 October 1954 \u2013 14 February 2019) was an Indian Politician from [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) who served as the [[List of Deputy Chief Ministers of Goa|Deputy Chief Minister]] of the Indian State of [[Goa]]. He contested from [[Mapusa (Vidhan Sabha constituency)]] as an independent unsuccessfully in 1989.\n\n==Biography==\nD'Souza was first elected to the [[Goa Legislative Assembly]] in 1999 as the [[Goa Rajiv Congress Party]]'s candidate and later in 2002, 2007, 2012 and 2017 as the [[BJP]] candidate from the [[Mapusa]] constituency.<ref>[http://www.goavidhansabha.gov.in/member-election-detail.php?id=67&flag=CM Shri. Francis Dsouza Previous Election Details | Goa Legislative Assembly<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He was appointed Deputy Chief Minister when BJP formed a government in 2012 under [[Manohar Parrikar]]'s leadership and remained [[List of Deputy Chief Ministers of Goa|Deputy Chief Minister]] when [[Laxmikant Parsekar]] became the Chief Minister. He was also front-runner to succeed [[Manohar Parrikar]] as the chief minister.<ref>[http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/goa-deputy-chief-minister-francis-dsouza-threatens-to-quit-if-not-made-chief-minister/1/399695.html Goa Deputy Chief Minister Francis D'Souza threatens to quit if not made CM]</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/politics/francis-dsouza-falls-in-line-parsekar-is-new-bjp-goa-cm/ | title=Laxmikant Parsekar sworn in as new Goa CM, Francis D\u2019Souza falls in line | date=9 November 2014 | first=Shalini | last=Nair | newspaper=The Indian Express | accessdate=27 November 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, he landed into a controversy after publicly declaring that [[India]] is a [[Hindu nationalism|Hindu nation]] and he was a ''Christian-Hindu''.<ref>{{cite news|title=India is already a Hindu nation: Goa Deputy CM Francis D\u2019Souza|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/07/india-is-already-a-hindu-nation-goa-deputy-cm-francis-dsouza/|accessdate=27 July 2014|agency=IANS|publisher=news.biharprabha.com|date=25 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nD'Souza died on 14 February 2019 at the age of 64 following a battle with cancer.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://goachronicle.com/goa-bjps-christian-face-francis-dsouza-no-more/ |title=Goa BJP's Christian face Francis D'Souza no more |date=2019-02-14 |website=Goa Chronicle |language=en-US |access-date=2019-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.devdiscourse.com/article/national/381692-francis-dsouza-former-goa-deputy-cm-bjp-mla-dies-at-64 |title=Francis D'Souza, former Goa deputy CM, BJP MLA dies at 64 |website=Devdiscourse News |language=en |access-date=2019-02-14}}</ref>\n\n== Positions held ==\n\n* 1985 - Elected as the Councillor of Mapusa Municipal Council.\n* 1986-1988 - President of Mapusa Municipal Council.\n* 1995 - Elected as the Councillor of Mapusa Municipal Council.\n* 1998-2000 Chairman of Mapusa Municipal Council.\n* 1999 - Cabinet Minister of Law, Election and Urban Development\n* 2000-2002 - Cabinet Minister of Judiciary and Labour & Employment till\n* 2002-2005 - Cabinet Minister of Information Technology, Law & Judiciary, Legislative Affairs and Craftsmen Training.\n* 2012-2014 - Cabinet Minister of Urban Development, Revenue and Craftsmen Training\n* 2014-2019 - Deputy Chief Minister, Cabinet Minister of Health, Revenue, Town and Country Planning, Urban Development and Law, Legislative Affairs\n* 2017-2019 - Cabinet Minister of Urban Development, Law and Judiciary, Legislative Affairs and Provedoria.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:D'Souza, Francis}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deputy chief ministers of Goa]]\n[[Category:People from Mapusa]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Goa]]\n[[Category:Goa MLAs 1999\u20132002]]\n[[Category:Goa MLAs 2002\u20132007]]\n[[Category:Goa MLAs 2007\u20132012]]\n[[Category:Goa MLAs 2012\u20132017]]\n[[Category:Goa MLAs 2017\u2013]]\n[[Category:Goa Rajiv Congress Party politicians]]\n\n\n\n{{BJP-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jaywardhan009", "label": "safe", "